    • Method Detail

      • invoke

        public Object invoke(Object proxy,
                     Method method,
                     Object[] args)
              throws Throwable
        This invoke method, requests computation from the ServerStart.

        It passes the Method, that is requested to be called, and wraps it, so that the parameters are contained, as well as the Class, which holds the Method.

        It then blocks, until a response is received from the Server, which contains the computed Result or an Exception. The Result may be null. If any Exception is send from the Server, this Exception will be rethrown.

        Whether or not an Exception will be thrown, is controlled by the IgnoreRemoteExceptions annotation.

        Since the computations are done by the Server, any CastException or wrong data type is filtered and replaced by a corresponding Exception. This might be ignored, in which case null is returned.

        Specified by:
        invoke in interface InvocationHandler
        Throws:
        Throwable
        See Also:
        JavaRemoteInformationInvocationHandler, IgnoreRemoteExceptions

      • setFallbackInstance

        public <S extends T> void setFallbackInstance(S fallbackInstance)
        Sets an Instance, that should be run, if the RemoteObject is not accessible.

        Whenever the RemoteObject is not accessible, this InvocationHandler will attempt to call the provided instance, until the RemoteObject is accessible again.

        Type Parameters:
        S - the type of the fallbackInstance, which must extend the Type of the Proxy.
        Parameters:
        fallbackInstance - the Runnable

      • executeFallback

        protected Object executeFallback(Throwable received,
                                 Method method,
                                 Object[] args)
                          throws InvocationTargetException,
                                 IllegalAccessException
        Executes the set Fallbacks.

        If no Fallback is accessible, a RemoteObjectNotRegisteredException will be thrown instead

        The return value depends on the set fallback. It will return:

        • A correct instance, if the Fallback is an instance
        • null, if the fallback is an runnable
        • nothing, else. In this case, an RemoteObjectNotRegisteredException will be thrown.
        Parameters:
        received - the Throwable received from the RemoteObject (might be null)
        method - the Method, that was invoked
        args - the Arguments, passed to the method-call
        Returns:
        the Result of the fallback execution. Might be null!
        Throws:
        InvocationTargetException - if the method within the fallback instance is not correctly invokable
        IllegalAccessException - if the fallback instance has changed the access rights to the method
